In C++, the name of an object normally refers directly to the storage holding the value. If you want a reference or an address you create that explicitly:

```cpp
Cls c;            // c is the actual object
auto &amp; rc = c;    // rc is a reference to c
auto * pc = &amp;c;   // pc holds the address of c
```

None of that has much to do with how you print an object though. You normally do that by overloading the `&lt;&lt;` operator:

```cpp
#include &lt;iostream&gt;

class Cls {
    int x;
    int y;
public:

   Cls(int x, int y) : x(x), y(y) {}

    friend std::ostream &amp;operator&lt;&lt;(std::ostream &amp;os, Cls const &amp;c) { 
        return os &lt;&lt; &quot;(&quot; &lt;&lt; c.x &lt;&lt; &quot;, &quot; &lt;&lt; c.y &lt;&lt; &quot;)&quot;;
    }
};

int main() {
    Cls x(1, 3);
    std::cout &lt;&lt; x &lt;&lt; &quot;\n&quot;;
}
```

Produces output like this:

```
(1, 3)
```

`operator&lt;&lt;` typically takes a reference to the object it&#39;s going to print. That&#39;s usually done to avoid making an unnecessary copy though, not because it&#39;s strictly necessary. Some types don&#39;t allow copying either, in which case passing by reference is necessary.

&quot;&lt;&lt;&quot; is a ostream operator that outputs data of a base-out type.Now that you define a class,you should overload &lt;&lt; operator(maybe it&#39;s hard for a beginner).And indeed how you define &lt;&lt;,what you output.
```cpp
#include &lt;iostream&gt;

class Cls
{
    //some var
